{"key":"post-14006116","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>14006116</id>\n<content>Not quite.&amp;nbsp; Leave the stirrer on.&amp;nbsp; The mycelium should be broken up with an eberbach and then put on LC if one chooses to go that route.&amp;nbsp; However, making LC from spores is much slower than inoculating grains, and then doing grain to grain transfers.&amp;nbsp; LC will also fail much more often and you have no way of knowing until you attempt to use it, several weeks down the road.&amp;nbsp; The rest of us will be eating mushrooms before your LC is ready to use.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Liquid favors bacteria as anyone who has used a spore syringe to inoculate agar plates has found out.&amp;nbsp; Squirting spores into sugar water has worse than a 50% failure rate, so I'm at a loss why people are still doing it.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>14006120</next>\n<prev>14006109</prev>\n<first>14006077</first>\n<last>14006744</last>\n<when>1298383510</when>\n<utime>02/22/11 04:05 PM</utime>\n</post>"}